I’ve been troubleshooting the NFS issues on the OCP-AI cluster and it looks like the root cause is related to jumbo frames on the storage VLANs.

Our storage bond (bnd0) on the masters is set to MTU 9000 and the NetApp ports are also at 9000. Small NFS operations work fine, but when NFS starts doing actual reads/writes it sends larger packets that rely on the full 9000 MTU path. Those packets appear to be getting dropped somewhere between the masters and the NetApp, which causes mounts and writes to hang.

I validated this with ping tests. A jumbo frame ping fails:

ping -I 10.172.194.152 -M do -s 8972 10.172.194.22 -c 3

But a standard MTU ping works without issues.

The -M do flag prevents fragmentation, so the packet has to pass through every hop at that size. If any port or trunk along the path is still at MTU 1500 it will drop the packet.

Could you trace the path from the master nodes through the fabric interconnects and storage switches to the NetApp and confirm MTU 9000 is set end-to-end for VLANs 1792–1798?

I’ve pinged you on Slack with the full reference list of node and NetApp LIF IPs for those VLANs.

For now I temporarily dropped the masters back to MTU 1500 so things are working again, but obviously that’s not ideal for NFS performance.

Let me know when you have a chance to take a look.

